Lupinus nootkatensis is a species of flowering plant in the pea family, Fabaceae. It is commonly known as the Nootka lupine or Alaska lupine.
The plant is characterized by its vibrant and bold display of purple-blue flowers, with a distinct shade of yellow in the center. 
The plant has a distinct palmate shape with five to twelve leaflets. 
Lupinus nootkatensis belongs to the genus of over 200 species, which are commonly found throughout the Americas. 
It originates from Alaska to British Columbia, and has been introduced into several countries including Norway, Iceland, and New Zealand. 
The plant is used in ecological restoration, agricultural production and as an ornamental plant in gardens. 
Lupinus nootkatensis is an important plant to many native pollinators and bees, and it also has food and medicinal uses.
